>
  <!-- Overview Section -->
  <section id="overview" class="content-section">
    <h2>The Unique Challenges of Maritime Insurance</h2>

    <p>
      Working offshore or at sea creates insurance complexities that land-based workers never face. You might be employed by a company in one country, working on a vessel registered in another, operating in the waters of a third—and your medical emergency could occur in international waters where no single country has clear jurisdiction.
    </p>

    <p>
      Add to this the physical realities: you're hours or days from a hospital, evacuation requires helicopters or ship diversions costing tens of thousands of dollars, and the work itself often involves hazards—heavy machinery, chemicals, extreme weather, and isolation. Standard international health insurance wasn't designed for these scenarios.
    </p>

    <p>
      Maritime workers need coverage that addresses evacuation from remote locations, understands the jurisdictional complexity of life at sea, covers occupational hazards specific to maritime work, and provides seamless care whether you're on a platform, in port, or home between rotations. Most importantly, you need clarity on who's responsible for what—before an emergency happens.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Worker Types Section -->
  <section id="worker-types" class="content-section">
    <h2>Types of Maritime Workers and Their Coverage</h2>

    <p>
      Maritime and offshore work encompasses vastly different roles, each with distinct insurance situations. A drilling engineer on a major oil platform has very different coverage than a deckhand on a private yacht. Understanding where you fit helps you identify gaps.
    </p>

    <ComparisonTable columns={workerColumns} rows={workerRows} />

    <p>
      <strong>Oil and gas workers</strong> typically have the most comprehensive employer coverage. Major energy companies provide robust health plans covering offshore medical facilities, helicopter evacuation, and onshore treatment. However, coverage quality varies between major operators and smaller contractors—if you work for a subcontractor, verify your actual coverage rather than assuming you're covered under the platform operator's plan.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Commercial shipping crew</strong> are usually covered through P&I (Protection and Indemnity) Clubs—mutual insurance associations that cover shipowners' liabilities, including crew medical expenses. The Maritime Labour Convention (MLC) 2006 sets minimum standards, but actual coverage varies. Filipino seafarers, who comprise about 25% of global maritime workforce, often have coverage through POEA-mandated insurance, though it may have significant limitations.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Cruise ship employees</strong> receive basic medical care from onboard medical facilities but often have limited coverage for serious conditions requiring shore-side treatment. Many cruise lines provide only basic coverage and repatriation—you may want supplemental insurance for comprehensive care.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Yacht crew and fishing workers</strong> often have the most precarious coverage situations. Private yacht crew may receive excellent coverage from generous owners or virtually nothing. Fishing vessel crews frequently work as independent contractors with no employer coverage, making personal insurance essential but difficult to obtain due to the hazardous nature of the work.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Employer Coverage Section -->
  <section id="employer-coverage" class="content-section">
    <h2>Understanding Employer-Provided Coverage</h2>

    <p>
      If you work for a major offshore operator or shipping company, you likely have employer coverage—but understanding exactly what it covers requires careful review. Don't assume your employer's coverage is comprehensive; maritime employer insurance often has significant limitations.
    </p>

    <h3>What Employer Coverage Typically Includes</h3>

    <p>
      Most reputable maritime employers provide coverage for work-related injuries and illnesses, emergency medical evacuation from offshore locations, treatment at designated medical facilities, and repatriation if you can't continue working. For oil and gas workers, this often includes access to onshore hospitals near major offshore hubs—Aberdeen, Houston, Stavanger, Perth—with established relationships with offshore operators.
    </p>

    <h3>Common Limitations to Watch For</h3>

    <p>
      <strong>Work-related only:</strong> Many maritime employer plans only cover conditions arising from work. A heart attack might be covered; a skiing injury during leave probably isn't. Some plans exclude "lifestyle" conditions or pre-existing conditions entirely.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Geographic restrictions:</strong> Your coverage may only apply while actively working offshore or in specific countries. Once you're home between rotations, employer coverage may not apply—especially problematic for workers who are home for extended periods.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Designated facilities only:</strong> Some plans require you to use specific hospitals or medical providers. Seeking care elsewhere—even in an emergency—may result in denied claims or reduced reimbursement.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Coverage gaps during transit:</strong> The journey to and from offshore locations can involve multiple countries and modes of transport. Verify whether you're covered during helicopter transfers, crew boats, and international travel to reach your worksite.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Coverage Gaps Section -->
  <section id="gaps" class="content-section">
    <h2>Identifying and Filling Coverage Gaps</h2>

    <p>
      Even with employer coverage, most maritime workers have insurance gaps. Identifying these gaps before you need care is essential—discovering you're uninsured during a medical emergency at sea is not the time to learn about coverage limitations.
    </p>

    <h3>Gap 1: Coverage Between Rotations</h3>

    <p>
      Offshore workers typically work rotation schedules—28 days on/28 days off, or similar patterns. Many employer plans only cover you while actively working, leaving you uninsured during your time home. If you're home for half the year, you need coverage for that half. Solutions include maintaining home country coverage (NHS for UK residents, for example), purchasing individual international health insurance with home country coverage, or negotiating year-round coverage as part of your employment package.
    </p>

    <h3>Gap 2: Non-Work-Related Conditions</h3>

    <p>
      Employer coverage for work-related conditions doesn't help when you develop appendicitis, need cancer treatment, or have a chronic condition requiring ongoing care. You need separate coverage for personal health issues. This is especially important for contractors and those with pre-existing conditions that employer plans may exclude.
    </p>

    <h3>Gap 3: Family Coverage</h3>

    <p>
      Maritime employer plans rarely cover dependents. Your family at home needs their own coverage—whether through the home country system, a spouse's employer, or individual policies. This becomes complex for multinational families where different members may have different nationality-based healthcare access.
    </p>

    <h3>Gap 4: Evacuation Benefit Limits</h3>

    <p>
      Some employer plans have caps on medical evacuation costs. A helicopter evacuation from a North Sea platform to Aberdeen might cost $30,000; from a remote platform requiring multiple aircraft, costs can exceed $100,000. Verify your evacuation benefit limits and consider supplemental evacuation coverage if limits are low.
    </p>

    <CTABox
      title="Coverage for Maritime Workers"
      description="Compare international health plans with evacuation coverage suitable for offshore and maritime workers."
      buttonText="Compare Plans"
      buttonHref="/compare"
      variant="highlight"
