  </section>

  <!-- Evacuation Section -->
  <section id="evacuation" class="content-section">
    <h2>Medical Evacuation: The Critical Coverage</h2>

    <p>
      For offshore and maritime workers, medical evacuation coverage isn't optional—it's essential. When you're working miles from shore, evacuation is the difference between receiving timely care and facing life-threatening delays. Understanding evacuation procedures and coverage is crucial.
    </p>

    <ComparisonTable columns={evacuationColumns} rows={evacuationRows} />

    <h3>How Offshore Evacuation Works</h3>

    <p>
      On oil platforms, the offshore medic or onshore medical team assesses whether evacuation is necessary. For emergencies, helicopters can typically reach North Sea platforms within 1-2 hours; Gulf of Mexico platforms are usually closer to shore. The decision to evacuate considers weather conditions—helicopters can't fly in severe storms, potentially delaying evacuation by days.
    </p>

    <p>
      For ships at sea, evacuation is more complex. Coast Guard helicopters have limited range; if you're mid-ocean, evacuation might require the ship diverting to meet a helicopter's range, or transfer to a passing vessel with better medical facilities. In truly remote locations, you might need to stabilize until reaching port—which could be days away.
    </p>

    <h3>Evacuation Coverage Considerations</h3>

    <p>
      <strong>Verify coverage limits:</strong> Some policies cap evacuation at $50,000 or $100,000. Complex evacuations can exceed these limits. Look for policies with $500,000+ evacuation coverage, or unlimited evacuation benefits.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Understand what triggers evacuation:</strong> Some policies only cover evacuation for "life-threatening" conditions, which can be interpreted restrictively. Better policies cover evacuation when "medically necessary" or when local facilities can't provide appropriate care.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Repatriation vs. evacuation:</strong> Evacuation gets you to the nearest appropriate facility; repatriation gets you home. These may be separate benefits with separate limits. A worker evacuated from a Gulf of Mexico platform to Houston might need separate repatriation coverage to return to their home in the UK.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Jurisdiction Section -->
  <section id="jurisdiction" class="content-section">
    <h2>Jurisdictional Complexity in Maritime Insurance</h2>

    <p>
      Maritime law is inherently international, and this complexity affects insurance. Where you're working, your employer's location, the vessel's flag state, and your nationality can all influence which laws apply and what coverage you're entitled to.
    </p>

    <ComparisonTable columns={jurisdictionColumns} rows={jurisdictionRows} />

    <h3>Flag State vs. Port State vs. Nationality</h3>

    <p>
      Ships are registered under "flag states"—often different from the owner's country. A ship might be owned by a Greek company, registered in Panama, crewed by Filipinos, and operating in Norwegian waters. Which country's laws apply? Generally, flag state law governs shipboard matters, but coastal states can enforce certain standards in their waters, and your employment contract determines most practical coverage questions.
    </p>

    <h3>The Maritime Labour Convention (MLC)</h3>

    <p>
      The MLC 2006, ratified by most major maritime nations, sets minimum standards for seafarer welfare, including health protection. Ships from ratifying countries must provide seafarers with health coverage at no cost, covering the period of service plus repatriation. However, MLC sets minimums—actual coverage may be limited, and enforcement varies.
    </p>

    <h3>US Workers: The Jones Act</h3>

    <p>
      US citizens working on US-flagged vessels have special protections under the Jones Act, which provides rights to sue employers for negligence and requires employers to provide "maintenance and cure"—essentially, medical care and living expenses until maximum recovery. This provides significant protections but doesn't eliminate the need for personal health coverage.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Shore Leave Section -->
  <section id="shore-leave" class="content-section">
    <h2>Coverage During Shore Leave and Port Calls</h2>

    <p>
      Maritime workers don't spend all their time at sea. Port calls, shore leave, and time between contracts create coverage situations that differ from active service. Understanding how your coverage works during these periods prevents unexpected gaps.
    </p>

    <h3>Port Call Medical Care</h3>

    <p>
      When ships call at ports, crew may need medical attention ashore. P&I Club coverage typically covers crew medical expenses in port, but there may be limitations on elective care or conditions that could wait until the next port. Some ports have better medical facilities than others—a medical issue in Singapore offers different options than one in a small Pacific island port.
    </p>

    <h3>Shore Leave Coverage</h3>

    <p>
      During shore leave, you're technically still employed, but your activities are personal. An injury during shore leave tourism might not be covered under work-related employer insurance. Check whether your coverage applies 24/7 while on the vessel or only during working hours—and what happens when you step ashore.
    </p>

    <h3>Between Contracts</h3>

    <p>
      Many maritime workers are employed on fixed-term contracts. Between contracts, employer coverage typically ends. This is especially relevant for cruise ship workers with seasonal contracts or seafarers waiting for their next ship assignment. Personal insurance or home country coverage becomes essential during these periods.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Family Section -->
  <section id="family-considerations" class="content-section">
    <h2>Family Coverage While You're at Sea</h2>

    <p>
      Maritime work creates unique family situations. You're away for weeks or months, often unreachable except by satellite communication. Your family needs coverage that works while you're at sea, and you need peace of mind that they're protected.
    </p>

    <h3>Coverage for Partners and Children</h3>

    <p>
      Maritime employer plans rarely cover dependents—you need separate family coverage. Options include home country public healthcare (NHS, national systems), partner's employer coverage if applicable, and individual or family international health insurance. The best choice depends on where your family lives, their healthcare needs, and your budget.
    </p>

    <h3>Emergency Communication</h3>

    <p>
      If a family emergency occurs while you're offshore, you need to know how you'll be contacted and what your options are. Understand your employer's emergency communication procedures, whether you can leave mid-rotation for family emergencies, and what coverage applies if you need to fly home suddenly.
    </p>

    <h3>Planning for Worst-Case Scenarios</h3>

    <p>
      Maritime work involves real risks. Ensure your family has clear documentation of all insurance policies, understands how to file claims, and knows who to contact for employer benefits. Life insurance and disability coverage are especially important for workers in hazardous industries.
    </p>

    <CTABox
      title="Coverage for Your Family"
      description="Find family health insurance options that work while you're at sea."
      buttonText="Explore Family Plans"
      buttonHref="/insurance-for/families"
    />
  </section>

  <!-- FAQ Section -->
  <section id="faq" class="content-section">
    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="faq-grid">
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Does my employer have to provide health insurance?</h3>
        <p>It depends on jurisdiction and your employment status. Ships from MLC-ratifying countries must provide health coverage for seafarers. Oil and gas operators typically provide coverage as standard. Yacht crew and fishing workers may have no employer obligation. Always verify coverage in writing before starting work.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>What if I get sick mid-voyage on a cargo ship?</h3>
        <p>Ships have medical supplies and officers trained in first aid. For serious conditions, options include diverting to port, helicopter evacuation (if within range), or ship-to-ship transfer. P&I Club coverage should cover evacuation costs, but verify your specific coverage. Stabilization until reaching port may be necessary for non-life-threatening conditions.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Can I buy personal insurance that covers offshore work?</h3>
        <p>Most standard health insurance policies exclude offshore work due to the hazardous nature and evacuation complexity. Specialized providers offer coverage for maritime workers, often as supplements to employer coverage. Expect higher premiums than standard international health insurance—but this coverage is essential if your employer coverage has gaps.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>I'm home between rotations for half the year. How do I get covered?</h3>
        <p>Options include home country coverage (NHS if UK resident, for example), international health insurance with home country coverage, or negotiating year-round employer coverage. Many offshore workers maintain multiple coverage sources—employer coverage while working, home country or personal coverage while home.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>What happens if I develop a condition that makes me unfit for offshore work?</h3>
        <p>This is a significant concern. Employer coverage typically ends when employment ends. If a medical condition prevents you from passing offshore medicals, you'll need personal coverage—which may be expensive or difficult to obtain with a new condition. Critical illness and income protection insurance are valuable supplements for offshore workers.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Do I need evacuation coverage if my employer provides it?</h3>
        <p>Review employer evacuation coverage limits and scope. If limits are capped (some policies limit at $50,000-100,000), consider supplemental evacuation coverage. Also verify whether evacuation applies only for work-related conditions or for any medical emergency—and whether it includes repatriation home or just to the nearest hospital.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Closing Section -->
  <section class="content-section">
    <h2>Securing Coverage for Life at Sea</h2>

    <p>
      Maritime and offshore work offers adventure and financial rewards, but it requires careful insurance planning. The combination of remote locations, hazardous conditions, and jurisdictional complexity means standard insurance approaches don't apply.
    </p>

    <p>
      Start by understanding exactly what your employer provides—in writing, not assumptions. Identify gaps in coverage for non-work conditions, family members, and periods between rotations. Then fill those gaps with appropriate personal coverage, understanding that maritime-specific insurance may cost more but is essential.
    </p>

    <p>
      Most importantly, don't wait until you're facing a medical emergency at sea to discover your coverage limitations. The time to sort out insurance is before you board the platform or ship—when you have options and can negotiate. Your workplace may be remote, but your coverage shouldn't leave you stranded.
    </p>

